There is a strong indication that the domestic debts profile of the Nigeria Government will be drastically reduced soon with the proposed settlement of some judgement debts owed litigants. In a document dated 28/2/2020 and signed by the former chief of staff to the president titled, “Liquidation of Judgement Debts On Behalf Of the Federal MDGs, States and Local Government,” there are hopes that the debts will soon be paid. LEADERSHIP reported yesterday how lawyers and other interested parties are excited over the plans by the federal government to clear the judgement debts through other options of debt settlement like issuance of bonds or promissory notes to enable the beneficiaries convert same to cash at discounted rates. The memo obtained by LEADERSHIP stated that a request was forwarded to the office of the Finance minister asking her to liaise with the Accountant General of the Federation and the Attorney General of the Federation and Minister of Justice to work out a modality for the payment of some of the debts. “Accordingly, you are kindly requested to engage the Federal ministry of justice to discuss and agree on a specific and appropriate funding proposal to inform the president’s directives on the relevant issue,” the memo said. It was gathered that  a document forwarded as cover to the memo explains that the payment is to be made pursuant to a judgment obtained in suit no FHC/ABJ/CS/148/20172017 which arose from a dispute in connection with the paris club debt refund. The beneficiaries are: Ned Munir Nwoko, Riok Nigeria LTD among others. The beneficiaries are excited about the government move and have acknowledged the federal government may not have the cash to meet the payment demands but said it will accept other options of debt settlement like issuance of bonds or promissory notes to enable the beneficiaries convert same to cash at discounted rates.